<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="description" content="The Future of the BBC" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission for the CMSSC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Friends of Radio 3 [FBB0025]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Friends of Radio 3 (FoR3) is a l</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">isteners’ group founded in 2003</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> with the aim of raising with the BBC issues which concern like-minded Radio 3 listeners. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We have a range of interests, including classical music, jazz, world music, drama, arts and discussion, but our</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> common interest is in preserving serious specialised a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">rts and music </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">programming</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> which we see as core to the BBC’s public service remit.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We have dealt with BBC management, the Governors and the Trust over </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the past ten years</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There are</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> 700-800 registered </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">FoR3 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">suppor</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ters. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">hen the BBC closed its online Radio 3 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">messageboards in 2010</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> for cost-cutting reasons</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> we set up The Radio 3 Forum as a replacement for interested members of the public. It currently has just over 1,400 registered members</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, only slightly (approximately 10%) overlapping with the FoR3 supporters</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">invited</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> forum members to contribute and discuss views on the Inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">topics</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We strongly support the concept of public service broadcasting and the continuance of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">an independent </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">BBC as the main provider. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">SUMMARY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The purpose of a public service broadcaster should be limited to the provision of public service content; as regards the BBC, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">such content to be defined in the Royal Charter and Agreement.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We favour a definition referred to by the House of Lords Communications Committee in 2009: “</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">content</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> that the market does not sufficiently provide</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">”, for example,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> “national and regional news, cur</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">rent affairs programmes, the arts, children's</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">programming, programmes dealing with religion and other beliefs and UK content"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">This is not intended to exclude a range of popular entertainment. Objectives set by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Ofcom</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> are not </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sufficiently </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">discr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">iminating. Quality and distinctiveness do not suffice to justify public funding</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">for BBC entertainment programming as a matter of policy. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">§1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The BBC has not adequately provided specialist educational content ‘</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">at all levels and for all ages’</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">(Agreement §7</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> b) ). Editorial strategy has focused across the board on ‘accessibility’: this has led to persistent claims of ‘dumbing down’ (§2.2). In the case of Radio 3, complaints from the commercial sector of ‘aping’ its rival have been ignored by management and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">di</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">smissed by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the Trust (§2.3).</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">legitimate </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">use of the BBC’s Freedom of Information derogation should be clarified</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> we </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">believe</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> it is often invoked unreasonably (§2.4); we are also unhappy </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">about the effects of outsourcing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> BBC Audience Services and Complaint</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s to a commercial </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">handling </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">agency (§2.5)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Public Commitments </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">are preferable to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> Public Purposes</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">; six suggested</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> commitments</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> based on public service content</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> (§3.3)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he BBC Trust</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">’s challenge to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> management </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">to examine ways in which</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the BBC could reduce its scope</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> practical difficulties;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the BBC is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">large</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and could focus some of its service more narrowly</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> (§4).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Allocation of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> services and funding disproportionate</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> centr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">entertainment for a wide audience;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">audiences with a special interest in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the arts in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">particular (and other minority interests) – which we consider to be core to the BBC’s public </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">service r</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">emit – are particularly </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">poorly </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">served:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">attempting to make</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> everything ‘accessible’ to everyone </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">does not serve</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> all audiences</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> (§5</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> Again, this leads to ‘dum</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">bing down’.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he BBC should play a leading role in developing and deploying new technologies (§8).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We considered four alternative ways of funding the BBC and our preference would be for general taxation, as being progressive and efficient (§9)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We do not agr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ee that the current model of governance is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">fit for purpose</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">failures have been </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">entirely </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the failures of individuals. The range of responsibilities laid upon the Trust means that they do not have the expertise and competence to exercise </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">complete</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">oversight of management. The appointment of a BBC ombudsman should be investigated (§12)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We support the continuance of the Charter and Agreement but believe that the Secretary of State should </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">equally</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> being bound </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> certain conditions (§13).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q1. What </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">purpose</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> of a public service broadcaster should be to broadcast public service content, as defined by the Royal Charter and Agreement: it should not be formulated i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">n terms of specific responsibilities. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We note the House of Lords </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Communications Committee’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">publication  ‘</span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200809/ldselect/ldcomuni/61/6103.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Public Service Broadcasting: short-term crisis, long-term</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> future?</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> (2009) which </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">outlined </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">various </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">definitions of public service broadcasting </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">which shared </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">common </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">features</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> definition</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">gaining support</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the Committee said,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> was "</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">content</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> that the market does not sufficiently provide”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ossible examples of such</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">content</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">would be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> “national and regional news, current affairs programmes, the arts, children's programming, programmes dealing with religion and other beliefs and UK content". </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> We support that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> interpretation of the core elements which we feel should form</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the basis of the BBC’s public service </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">content</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he Committee</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">stated</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">: “</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">[N]either Ofcom's nor the BBC's set of objectives is sufficiently discriminating to distinguish between those programmes and services that merit public finance and special </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">regulatory treatment and those that do not. Few programmes screened by any UK broadcaster would not satisfy at least one of the objectives.” We suggest alternative objectives (§3.3 below).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2006</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm67/6763/6763.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">White Paper</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">differentiated</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> between </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> “worthy”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and the en</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">tertaining.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We accept the point that the “worthy” should not be the sole type of content, but the choice of word is unfortunate (= “all very well in its way, but…”): the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">informative and educational may well be entertaining, but that is not its primary purpose</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> It should be acknowledged that quality and distinctiveness alone do not give  BBC entertainment the right to be publicly funded: if that were the case, much commerci</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">al entertainment would also merit such funding.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q2. How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It is impossible to take an overview of all services but, regarding Radio 3,  it seems to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> us</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> as listeners</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> that financial cuts have </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">been disproportionate, to the detriment of some </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">quality of content. This may not apply across the board</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> where funding has been maintained, or even increased</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The Agreement §7,</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> ‘Promoting education and learni</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ng’, states:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In developing (and reviewing) the purpose remit for promoting education and learning, the Trust must, amongst other things, seek to ensure that the</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> BBC—</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">a) stimulates interest in, and knowledge of, a full range of subjects and issues through </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">content that is accessible and can encourage either formal or informal</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">learning; and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">b) provides specialist educational content and accompanying material to facilitate learning at all levels and for all ages.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Here, a) and b) above are not </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">either/or</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">both/and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. If everything is ‘accessible’ to everyone, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all levels</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">are not catered for.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> The BBC has focused on making programming ‘accessible’, but p</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">eople who seek to deepen their knowledge of their special areas of interest have not been well catered for. </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">is, and the BBC’s indiscriminate use of ‘interactivity’ – inappropriate for specialist services and programmes</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> – trivialise content and contribute to the frequently expressed impression that the corporation is ‘dumbing down’ in an attempt to make all prog</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">rammes appealing to all audiences.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There have been some complaints, which we would support, of BBC services copying commercial rivals,  contrary to §3.1.7 of the 2006 White Paper, and the Charter and Agreement. The Trust has been disinclined to respond</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Freedom of Information: We have been dissatisfied with the BBC’s operation of its FOI derogation, nominally in respect of ‘journalism, art and literature’, but </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">interpreted as</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> anything connected, however loosely, with programm</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e making</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and content. The</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> dividing line between what was intended to fall</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, legitimately,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> outside the scope of the Act and the public interest </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">disclosure</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">seems to be a matter of BBC convenience. The appeals procedure is in practice too cumbersome</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to offer a remedy</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We are c</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">oncerned </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">that, n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">otwithstanding the cost-efficiency argument, submission of regular reports and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">audience satisfaction surveys,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the outsourcing of BBC Audience Services and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Complaints to a private agency results in a service too remote from</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to provide satisfactory responses</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q3. Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We prefer the concept of ‘Public Service </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Commitments’</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">providing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> specified content and services</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, not achieving vag</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ue, unquantifiable outcomes (“Sustaining citizenship &amp;c”)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In particular, it</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> should be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">clear that there is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">no implied </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">obligation</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> on the BBC to ‘deliver its purposes’ effectively by ‘reaching as many licence fee payers as possible’.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> This becomes a prete</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">xt</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to focus on </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">boosting </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ratings </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">which is not a healthy contribution to the market</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3.3.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sacrifice the admirable succinctness of the Public Purposes to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> offer these expanded Commitments:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">i) To deliver international, national and local news in an accurate,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> balanced and impartial way; to provide informed analysis and a plurality of views to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">promote</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> an intelligent understanding of UK society and world affairs</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, both to UK and world audiences  (through the World Service)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ii) To provide a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">broad </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">range of mainst</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ream entertainment, from the UK and the world</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">serve</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> all ages</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">; to provide</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> cultural </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and educational programming at all levels, including</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> specialised programmes </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">aimed at </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">extend</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> tastes and interests, and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> deepen</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and appreciation</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">iv) To rec</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ognise and provide for the needs and requirements of a demographically, culturally and geographically diverse public. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">v) To be mindful of the BBC's position in the ecology of UK broadcasting, not competing with what the commercial sector is already </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">providing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">vi) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">To be a leader in developing and using new technologies and new ways of delivering output for the benefit of the public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Service licences should then </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">refine</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the special remits of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">each service</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q4. What scope, scale and remit should the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">BBC have?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">4.1 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The BBC Trust’s introduction to the Director-General’s 2010 Strategy Review asked the Executive where the BBC’s focus and scale could be reduced “if necessary”. </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The Executive response was contained in the section entitled ‘Doing fewer</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> things better’</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> which recommended prioritising some areas and recommending some </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">service closures (some of whic</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">h materialised, others did not, demonstrating the difficulty of cutting services which audiences value greatly). It may be that some services, fo</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">r example Radio 2, can afford to become more focused and specialist at the risk of losing audience (as the Trust implied).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The BBC is almost certainly larger than it needs to be, but this invites the question as to how large the BBC ‘needs to be’ to f</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ulfil its mission. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We would welcome a better balance between the content  areas: information, education and entertainment, both in terms of broadcast hours and of funding (see 5.3 below). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q5 Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> or lesser degree for particular audiences?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">5.1 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It appears to be accepted that the BBC should devote the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> largest</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> part of its resources to the services and output which appeal to the largest number of people (this has been stated by th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Trust </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> “to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">pr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">otect the services that deliver the greatest value to large parts of the audience</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">” – DQF proposals).</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">However, that leave</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> many other ‘minority’ audiences – demographic, cultural, ethnic – who enjoy </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">mainstream</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> output to a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">much </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">lesser degree</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> or possibly not at all. They will prefer content which – for a variety of  reasons – is not considered interesting, relevant or entertaining by the majority of the general public</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. Such audiences should be served adequately.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We think that ‘fair’ and ‘a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ppropriate’, having regard to what are considered core elements of public service broadcasting, are preferable to ‘proportionate’. In terms of television spend, 61% for BBC One, 22%  for BBC Two and 2.7% for BBC Four does not seem ‘fair’, ‘appropriate’ or </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">even ‘proportionate’ for a public service broadcaster. BBC radio </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">funding is</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> similar</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ly discrepant</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, the service</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">licence spend of Radio 3 (</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the only one of the five network stations to have</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> no digital only ‘sister’ station) being the lowest of the BBC network </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">stations</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, to cover what is arguably the most varied and expensive remit in terms of specialist musics and speech/arts programmes</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">5.4</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We object to the crude </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">demographic</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> argument that ‘older listeners’ are overserved or at least adequately served. </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We totall</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">y support special children’s services, but in terms of separate, differentiated services, younger audiences (children and young adults) are, by comparison, well served in terms of both services and funding (CBeebies, CBBC, BBC Three, Radio 1, Radio 1Xtra, </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">plus to an extent, the Asian Network and 6 Music). Adult audiences are overwhelmingly treated as ‘general audiences’ and anything ‘new’ or ‘serious’ is treated at an intellectually elementary (‘accessible’) level e.g. Radio 3 is more concerned to introduce</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> new listeners to classical music than to cater for its existing music audience.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q6 What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to provide?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Quality, value for money and creative</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> opportunities are clearly considerations but this is not of immediate relevance to audiences. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q7. How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It seems right that programmes which have been paid for by the licence fee payer should be marketed commercially in such a way as to provide a return which can</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> be reinvested to fund further programming.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q.8  What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of delivering output?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">8.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The BBC has traditionally played a leading role in developing new technologies. We believe it to be in the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">licence fee payers’ interests that this should continue, delivering new opportunities to enjoy BBC content.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">8.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The BBC should stay at the forefront and maintain an understanding of the possibilities that are being developed elsewhere.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q 9. How should the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> BBC be funded beyond 2016?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">9.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We discussed four main possibilities: a) advertising</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> revenue  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">b) subscription  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">c)  TV licence fee  d) general taxation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-33pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">9.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Advertising was rejected for three reasons. Firstly, audiences appreciate a service without advert</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ising and already complain about the amount of BBC on-air promotion. Secondly, the commercial imperatives of advertising would inevitably increase the pressure on programme makers always to appeal to the largest possible a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">udience, something we believe has </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">already become</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> detrimental to the BBC’s core public service broadcasting. Thirdly,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">we estimated that the amount of revenue needed to fund the BBC from advertising would begin to approach double the amount of advertising currently </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in evidence</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in the region</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> of £4</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">bn</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> p.a.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">for television</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">). The appearance of a giant such as the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> have a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> colossal impact on the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> market</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">9.3</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Subscription was not favoured because the detail </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">was hard to guess:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">whether</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> individual service</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">requ</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ire a separate subscription, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">how they might be bundled,  h</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ow the orchestras and Proms </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">would be funded (</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">if added to a service like Radio 3 that would make it impossibly unattractive to subscribers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">9.4</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The licence fee has served the BBC well over the years but the inescapable fact is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">that it is an inherently regressive mechanism for raising funds, with the burden falling disproportionately on the poor</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">/women</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> who bear the brunt of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">prosecutions,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> fines and ultimately imprisonment if they cannot pay the fines.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">9.5</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">One considered benefit of the licence fee has been the link between the fee  paid and programmes watched, but this becomes a disadvantage as people increasingly use subscription services or commercial services only. The fee they pay is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">linked to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">BBC services which they do not use.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">9.6</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Funding the BBC from general taxation has appeal: it is fair because</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> it is</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">  income-related; the mechanism for calculating and collecting the tax from individuals already exists; it avoids the need for – and expense o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">f – TV Licensing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and its related responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q10  Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond the BBC?</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">10.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Yes. Public service content should be considered a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">valuable</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> ‘public good’</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, but it is expensive</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">receive public funding.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q11 What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">11.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Comparisons as regards standards and range of content will depend on what is being compared. However, with overseas rad</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">io services now available online these are being </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">increasingly</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> accessed via the internet by Radio 3 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">music </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">listeners</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> who feel the BBC no longer serves their requirements</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">11.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Discussions on our public forum indicate that listeners are keen to recommend and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to hear of recommended se</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">rvices.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q12</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">12.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The last government’s new model for the governance of the BBC  has been in operation for less than seven years. The Charter put in place </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">a new framework by which the BBC, especially the BBC Executive, could be held to account in the interests of the licence fee payer, the BBC Trust being the sovereign body charged with protecting the interests of the public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">12.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Our own experience relates </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">most closely to the way in which the new system of service licences and reviews (remits, content and editorial direction of the individual services) has been overseen by the Trust. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">12.3</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The Trust issues the service licences; approves update</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s, carries out </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">service reviews and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> public consultations</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and approves management strategies. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">At present the Trust seems both too remote to have sufficient knowledge and competence, and therefore too reliant on information from</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> managers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. That is a flaw of both the system </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and the individuals.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">12.4</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">here is notionally an official procedure for complaining about a Trust action or decision, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in practice this consists of submitting the details to the Director of the Trust</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> Unit for an oracular adjudication</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> no </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">transparen</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">t procedure. Lord Grade has</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> urged the appointment of a BBC ombudsman, a measure which we </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">think should be investigated.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q13 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">13.1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In principle, the Charter and Agreement seem appropriate. Whether ten years is the appropriate length of time might depend how far it is immutable from one 10-year period to the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">next.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> It is in the interests of the BBC to have time to plan.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">13.2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, for the Government, should also be bound by certain</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> undertakings</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he Agreement allows the Government to make significant changes</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> during the life of each Charter</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. Th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e 2006 Agreement, for example, states:</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> “For the purposes of the World Service, the Foreign Secretary shall, in each year, pay to the BBC out of money provided by Parliament such sum as the Treasury may authorise.”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">  Yet the funding arrangements </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">could be</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> ch</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">anged in 2010.</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> There could also have been a change in the funding for the over-75s’ licence fee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">A public service for all: the BBC in the digital age</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">, March 2006,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> §3.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">1.6: </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">“</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">Enter</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">tainment is a vital part of the </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">BBC’s mission. The Government sees no conflict between the new arrangements and entertainment. In line with the view of the special Lords Select Committee on Charter Review, we do not subscribe to the idea that </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">public service broadcasting should be confined to the “worthy”. Indeed, in most cases the BBC’s output will achieve its maximum impact only by entertaining its viewers and listeners.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h5 style="margin:0.1pt 0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold"> "</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal">Who listens to this codswallop? Hasn't it occurred to the Director G</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal">eneral of the BBC, the Chairman of the BBC Trust, any of the free-lunching BBC Trustees, or the Department for Culture, Media and Sport that interacting with the public in this way is simply a substitute for having something to say?"</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal"> Stuart Nicholson, </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Jazz</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">wise</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal">, Dec</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal">. 2013</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal">/Jan. 2014, p.17</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal">,‘The Way It Is’.</span></h5><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">“Jane Clancey, research account head for BBC audio and music, defended the commercial impact of the corporation's radio output. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">She said the BBC's duty was to reach as many licence fee payers as possible</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/media/news/a95062/local-commercial-radio-audiences-suffer.html#ixzz2lCR8aReS"><span style="color:#003399; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/media/news/a95062/local-commercial-radio-audiences-suffer.html#ixzz2lCR8aReS</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Where if necessary</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> could the BBC’s focus be </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">narrowed and its scale reduced?                    </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“After a period of successful year-on-year efficiency savings across the whole BBC, there now needs to be some </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">radical thinking about either reducing the number/reach of services </span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">or in clarifying their boundaries to focus on some clear priorities. […] How could the current scale of the BBC be reassessed? […]</span><span style="color:#1a1718; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">                                                                                               </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“Management should also be guid</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ed by the principle that the BBC should be no bigger than it needs to be to fulfil its mission</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">.”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">  </span><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/assets/files/pdf/review_report_research/strategic_review/strategy_review.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">BBC Strategy Review, March 2010, p. iv</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">  </span><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/assets/files/pdf/review_report_research/strategic_review/strategy_review.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">Strategy Review, pp 35-44</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">An Agreement Between Her Majesty’s Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport and the Britis</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">h Broadcasting Corporation</span><span style="color:#141413; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">, July 2006, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Treasury Minute, p. ii</span></p></body></html>